## Adjacent Code — How the `plugin:initialized` Event Is Fired

From `packages/framework/arbor/src/arbor.ts` lines 180–202:

```typescript
// Fire plugin:initialized for all kits before starting any apparatus
for (const kit of kits) {
  await fireEvent(eventHandlers, 'plugin:initialized', kit);
}

// Start each apparatus in dependency order
const startupCtx = buildStartupContext(eventHandlers);
for (const app of orderedApparatuses) {
  if (app.apparatus.provides !== undefined) {
    provides.set(app.id, app.apparatus.provides);
  }

  await app.apparatus.start(startupCtx);

  if (!provides.has(app.id) && app.apparatus.provides !== undefined) {
    provides.set(app.id, app.apparatus.provides);
  }

  await fireEvent(eventHandlers, 'plugin:initialized', app);
}
```

**Key insight:** All standalone kits fire `plugin:initialized` BEFORE any apparatus starts. So when the Spider's `start()` calls `g.kits()`, it gets all standalone kits. All kits have already fired `plugin:initialized` before any apparatus subscription is set up. Therefore the explicit `g.kits()` scan at startup is necessary (not just the event handler).

For apparatus: `plugin:initialized` fires for each apparatus AFTER it starts. By the time Spider's `start()` runs, stacks/clerk/fabricator have already started and fired their `plugin:initialized`. So if any of them has `rigTemplates` in their `supportKit`, Spider needs a "Phase 1b" scan to catch them.

